<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="ops-customer-support">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>gtm-strategist</domain>
    <summary>Self-serve-first support hierarchy for solopreneurs. Build FAQ and knowledge base before adding async channels, define SLA tiers, use weekly ticket pattern reviews to feed product improvements.</summary>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-29</created>
    <tags>
      <tag>customer-support</tag>
      <tag>support-ops</tag>
      <tag>sla</tag>
      <tag>product-feedback</tag>
      <tag>customer-success</tag>
    </tags>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Customer Support</title>

    <summary>A self-serve-first support hierarchy for solopreneurs: build FAQ and knowledge base before adding any async channel, define SLA tiers by plan (Free = 24-48h, Paid = 4-24h, Enterprise = 1-4h), and use weekly ticket pattern reviews to feed product improvements. The rule: if the same question is asked 5+ times, add it to the FAQ; if the same bug is reported repeatedly, prioritize the fix.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>70-85% of support volume can be deflected by a well-built FAQ and knowledge base. Responding to the first ticket from any paying customer within 4 hours — regardless of SLA tier — reduces churn risk at the critical early-adoption stage. Ticket category patterns are a direct product signal: if how-to tickets for a specific feature exceed 20% of volume, that feature needs UX work, not more documentation. Agents must never promise specific fixes or timelines without human confirmation.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Setting up the first support system (self-serve docs, email SLAs, templates)</item>
        <item>Drafting or updating a support policy document</item>
        <item>Conducting a weekly support review: pattern extraction, FAQ gap identification</item>
        <item>Mining ticket export for product insight (recurring pain points → roadmap)</item>
        <item>Drafting template responses for the top recurring question types</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Real-time live chat or voice support — requires a human in the loop, not an agent</item>
        <item>Legal or financial issues raised via support — escalate immediately</item>
        <item>Incidents affecting all users (outages, data loss) — use incident response process</item>
        <item>Sensitive topics (account termination, fraud) — human judgment required</item>
        <item>Sending any response that includes a refund, credit, or plan change without human approval</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="self-serve-first-rule">
      <rule>
        <statement>Build FAQ and knowledge base before adding any async support channel. 70-85% of support volume can be deflected by a well-built self-serve layer.</statement>
        <rationale>Every ticket that reaches a human could have been answered by documentation. Self-serve assets scale infinitely; human support does not. Building it first prevents backlog from the first day.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>If the same question is asked 5+ times, add it to the FAQ immediately. If the same bug is reported repeatedly, prioritize the fix over any other support activity.</statement>
        <rationale>Recurring tickets indicate a product or documentation gap. Answering the same question repeatedly without fixing the root cause is an inefficient use of support time.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good">
        <note>Solopreneur SaaS with 50 knowledge base articles: 70% self-service resolution, 30 tickets/week handled in 5 hours total, 4.7/5 CSAT. Self-serve investment paid back in under 2 months.</note>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="sla-tiers">
      <rule>
        <statement>Respond to the first ticket from any paying customer within 4 hours regardless of SLA tier. First impressions determine churn risk at the critical early-adoption stage.</statement>
        <rationale>New paying customers form their support experience opinion within the first interaction. A fast first response builds confidence that the product is maintained.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Free users: 24-48 hours response time</item>
        <item>Paid (low tier): 4-24 hours</item>
        <item>Paid (high tier): 4 hours + live chat during business hours</item>
        <item>Enterprise: 1-4 hours + dedicated support contact</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="escalation-path">
      <list>
        <item>Level 1: Self-service (docs, FAQ)</item>
        <item>Level 2: Standard support (email or async chat)</item>
        <item>Level 3: Technical escalation (founder or senior engineer)</item>
        <item>Level 4: Emergency (product down, data loss — incident process, not support queue)</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>Legal, financial, fraud, and data deletion requests must route directly to human queue. Agents must never handle these automatically.</statement>
        <rationale>These topics have regulatory implications (GDPR, PCI-DSS, consumer protection law) that require human judgment and legal accountability.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ticket-categorization">
      <rule>
        <statement>Categorize every ticket as: bug-blocking (critical), bug-non-blocking (high), how-to (medium), feature-request (low), general-feedback (low). Track volume by category weekly.</statement>
        <rationale>Category distribution is a leading product signal. How-to tickets above 20% of volume for a specific feature indicate a UX problem, not a documentation gap.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>If how-to tickets for a specific feature exceed 20% of volume, that feature needs UX work. More documentation for a confusing flow does not fix the confusion.</statement>
        <rationale>Documentation treats the symptom. Fixing the UX removes the root cause and permanently reduces support load for that flow.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="resolution-metrics">
      <list>
        <item>First response time target: under 4 hours (shows attentiveness)</item>
        <item>Resolution time target: under 24 hours</item>
        <item>First contact resolution target: above 70% (efficiency signal)</item>
        <item>CSAT target: above 4.5/5</item>
        <item>Tickets per customer over time: should be decreasing (product improvement signal)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="communication-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Never let an agent send a response with a specific commit, deadline, or "we will fix this by [date]" — those require human sign-off on feasibility.</statement>
        <rationale>Commitment to a deadline without verifying engineering capacity creates a new customer expectation that, if missed, causes more churn than the original bug.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>Bug report: "Thanks for reporting. I'll look into this." — not "That shouldn't happen"</item>
        <item>Feature request: "Great idea. I've added it to our list." — not "We won't build that"</item>
        <item>Angry customer: "I understand the frustration. Let me fix this." — not "Calm down"</item>
        <item>User error: "Easy to miss. Here's how it works..." — not "You did it wrong"</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-guardrails">
      <rule>
        <statement>Agents must not mark tickets as resolved automatically. Only draft the response; resolution confirmation requires human action.</statement>
        <rationale>A ticket marked resolved without customer confirmation produces a false CSAT signal and may leave the customer's issue unresolved, increasing churn risk.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Inject tone guidelines explicitly: "friendly, empathetic, first-person" for consumer products. Agents default to neutral-formal, which underperforms for consumer support.</statement>
        <rationale>Tone mismatch in support responses reduces CSAT and increases escalations. Consumer customers expect warmth; enterprise customers expect professionalism. Both require explicit guidance.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>An agent can own the weekly support review cycle end-to-end if given a structured ticket export: ingest the export, categorize tickets by type (bug / how-to / feature request / billing), count patterns, flag the top three recurring issues, and generate a draft review document with suggested FAQ additions. A second agent pass can draft template responses for the top recurring questions. Human review is required before publishing any new FAQ article or sending templated responses.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-constraints">
      <p>Agents cannot access live ticket data without integration to Intercom, Zendesk, or Help Scout APIs. Automated responses risk sounding generic; personalization requires injecting customer context (plan, history). CSAT measurement requires a survey tool; agents cannot measure satisfaction directly. Pattern detection from tickets requires a structured export — agents cannot browse a ticketing UI. Agents must not promise specific fixes or timelines without human confirmation of feasibility.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="support-tools-and-services">
      <p>Intercom (SaaS, REST API) provides conversations, notes, tags, and webhook for new tickets. Zendesk (SaaS, REST API) offers full ticket lifecycle and bulk export. Help Scout (SaaS, REST API) is simpler than Zendesk and good for solopreneurs. Crisp (SaaS, REST API) is affordable and includes knowledge base and chat. Linear (SaaS, REST/GraphQL) can convert bug tickets to issues automatically. For pattern detection, use jq to parse JSON ticket exports or miller (mlr) to aggregate CSV exports by category.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices-summary">
      <list>
        <item>Build self-serve (FAQ, knowledge base) before adding any async support channel — agents can draft articles from existing ticket data</item>
        <item>Respond to the first support ticket from any paying customer within 4 hours regardless of SLA tier; first impressions determine churn risk</item>
        <item>Keep response templates in a structured format (YAML or JSON) so agents can select and fill them programmatically without reformatting</item>
        <item>Use ticket categories as product signals: if how-to tickets for a specific feature exceed 20% of volume, that feature needs UX work, not more documentation</item>
        <item>Set explicit support hours in the product UI and auto-reply; an agent can generate the out-of-hours message automatically</item>
        <item>Never let an agent send a response with a specific commit, deadline, or "we will fix this by [date]" — those require human sign-off</item>
        <item>Agents may hallucinate product behavior if given only the ticket text without current product documentation as context</item>
        <item>Sensitive tickets (billing disputes, data deletion requests) must never be handled automatically — build a hard filter to route these to human queue</item>
        <item>GDPR/data privacy: ticket data often contains PII; agents processing it must run in an environment with appropriate data handling controls</item>
        <item>Tone calibration: agents default to neutral-formal; for consumer products, inject explicit tone guidelines ("friendly, empathetic, first-person")</item>
        <item>Human-in-loop checkpoint: any response that includes a refund, credit, or plan change must be queued for human approval before sending</item>
        <item>Agents should not mark tickets as resolved automatically — only draft the response; resolution confirmation requires human action</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/support-policy.md" purpose="Support policy doc: channels, SLA by plan, escalation contacts"/>
      <template path="templates/weekly-review.md" purpose="Weekly support review: volume, performance, top issues, action items"/>
      <template path="templates/email-acknowledgment.md" purpose="First-response acknowledgment email template"/>
      <template path="templates/email-resolution.md" purpose="Resolution email template with step-by-step fix format"/>
      <template path="templates/ticket-patterns.py" purpose="Count tickets by category from CSV export; output weekly summary"/>
    </templates>

